flowRoot.flowPara: • The visualization was produced using the JHAVÉ project, since is has a focus on user engagement.
• These numbers can be given in either decimal or binary values, and the window will automatically convert between the two bases for the user's convenience.
• Automatic register sizing or fixed register size is also available, and erroneous input is flagged and the window auto-corrects the values.
• Questions are designed to address lower to middle levels of understanding, as defined by Bloom's Taxonomy.
• Examples of questions at the 'Knowledge' and Comprehension' level include case identification and result prediction
• At the 'Applying' level, students are asked questions which require they understand the relation of the final product and current values in the registers
• JHAVÉ's 'input generator' feature allows students to generate values for the visualization.
• JHAVÉ treats the algorithm as a series of snapshots. Users can navigate forwards and backwards in the visulization at their liesure.
• In the psuedocode display the currently executing line is highlighted to correspond with the visualization.
• These snapshots are accompanied on the right by a psuedocode display.
• In particular it provides facility for uster to View, Respond to, and Change parameters of the visualization.

flowRoot.flowPara: We have plans to:
• Implement a set of exercises for the visualization with automated assessment, linked from the hypertextbook
• Perform an empirical study to determine the effectiveness of the modules
• Add feedback feature to JHAVÉ for incorrect
answers to questions
• Develop related modules for more advanced algorithms for signed binary multiplication
• Develop a related module that covers signed binary division
• Constructivist theory of learning influenced our approach for our hypertextbook. We use the student's pre-exiting knowledge as the basis for teaching the algorithm
• Our literature search turned up few visualizations for the topic of binary multiplication in computer organization

• One visualization at http://www.frontiernet.net/~prof_tcarr/Multiplication/applet.html allows for step-by-step viewing and limited questions. Ours includes a discussion of hardware, signed values, and Booth's Algorithm

• Others at http://www.ecs.umass.edu/ece/koren/arith/simulator/ inlcuded several algorithms and are linked to a commercial textbook. Our visualization seeks to actively engage the learner, and our textbook is available for free online.
• We created two modules, an online text or hypertext resource and an engaging visualization of the algorithm
• Our intent was to design the modules to work well together, but allow each to stand on its own.
• We chose Booth's Multiplication Algorithm for its versatility for allowing discussion of math and hardware.
• Multiplication of signed numbers is not always taught in computer organization courses
• Some textbooks do not provide any coverage
• Those that do vary significantly in approach and method
• Texbooks do not always cover both the mathematical background and the hardware implementation details
• Time prohibitive for professors to develop this material
• Limitations on classroom time may restrict adding new material
ls
• The format is based on constructivist theory of learning, taking into account and building on their previous knowledge
• The hypertextbook begins with a discussion of binary multiplication as repeated addition
• Then the shift-and-add method of multiplication is introduced
• We then introduce hardware design issues, which leads to the shift-and-add binary multiplication method in hardware.
• Then the problems with signed binary numbers are addressed
• Booth's algorithm is introduced, along with a mathematical justification for why it works
• We then explain Booth's algorithm from a hardware perspective
• The textbook concludes with questions and exercises to test student's understanding, as well as a link to our visualization
